---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import styles from '../../styles/GuidePage.module.css';

const pageTitle = 'Leap Years and Age Calculation: The February 29 Edge Case | Age Calculator Pro';
const pageDescription =
  'How leap years affect age calculation, what happens to a February 29 birthday in a non-leap year, and how the Gregorian rule with its 400-year exception actually works.';
const pageKeywords = 'leap year age, february 29 birthday, gregorian leap year rule, leap year calculator';
const canonical = 'https://agecalculatorpro.app/guides/leap-years-and-age-calculation';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Leap Years and Age Calculation: The February 29 Edge Case',
  description: pageDescription,
  datePublished: '2026-06-23',
  dateModified: '2026-06-23',
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Age Calculator Pro Editorial Team',
    url: 'https://agecalculatorpro.app/about-us',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Age Calculator Pro',
    logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: 'https://agecalculatorpro.app/favicon.svg' },
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: canonical,
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={pageTitle}
  description={pageDescription}
  keywords={pageKeywords}
  canonical={canonical}
  schemas={[schema]}
>
  <Header />

  <main>
    <section class={styles.hero}>
      <div class="container">
        <h1>Leap Years and Age Calculation: The February 29 Edge Case</h1>
        <p>
          A leap-day birthday sounds like a fun quirk. It also happens to be one of the most common places age-calculation code
          gets things wrong. This guide explains the rules, the edge cases, and how our engine handles them.
        </p>
        <div class={styles.metaRow}>
          <span class={styles.badge}>Editorial team</span>
          <span class={styles.badge}>Published June 23, 2026</span>
          <span class={styles.badge}>6 min read</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <div class="container">
        <article class={`card ${styles.article}`}>
          <h2>Why leap years exist at all</h2>
          <p>
            Earth takes about 365.2422 days to orbit the sun. A 365-day calendar year drifts by roughly a quarter of a day every
            year, which adds up to a full day every four years. If left alone, the seasons would slowly slide out of sync with
            the calendar over centuries.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Julian calendar addressed this with a simple rule: add a leap day every four years. This over-corrected slightly,
            because 365.25 is a hair more than the true orbital period. The Gregorian reform in 1582 refined the rule further:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Every year divisible by 4 is a leap year.</li>
            <li>Except years divisible by 100 - those are not leap years.</li>
            <li>Except years also divisible by 400 - those <em>are</em> leap years.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            So 1900 was not a leap year, but 2000 was. And 2100 will not be, even though 2096 and 2104 will. Our calculator follows
            the Gregorian rule strictly, which is the same convention used by every mainstream operating system and browser.
          </p>

          <h2>What happens to a February 29 birthday</h2>
          <p>
            The tricky question is: if you were born on February 29, when do you celebrate in a non-leap year? Legally, jurisdictions
            handle this differently.
          </p>

          <div class={styles.tableWrap}>
            <table class={styles.table}>
              <thead>
                <tr><th>Approach</th><th>Where it is common</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Celebrate March 1</td><td>UK, Hong Kong, and much of the common-law world</td><td>Age increments on March 1 in non-leap years.</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Celebrate February 28</td><td>Taiwan, New Zealand (in some contexts)</td><td>Age increments on February 28 in non-leap years.</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Age only on real leap days</td><td>Cultural convention among some "leaplings"</td><td>Person only ages up every four years - fun trivia, not law.</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p>
            Our engine picks a consistent, defensible choice: on non-leap years, a February 29 birthday is considered to occur on
            March 1 for the purpose of the whole-year rollover. This matches the majority common-law convention and gives an answer
            that is generally acceptable on official forms. If your jurisdiction uses the February 28 convention, subtract one day
            from your result.
          </p>

          <h2>How the year count itself is affected</h2>
          <p>
            Once whole years are correctly counted, the day count naturally accommodates extra leap days. Suppose you were born on
            January 1, 2000 - a leap year. By January 1, 2020, you have lived exactly 20 calendar years and 7,305 days. That is
            365 &times; 20 = 7,300, plus 5 extra days for the leap years in 2000, 2004, 2008, 2012, and 2016. (2020 has not yet
            added its extra day by January 1.)
          </p>

          <p>
            The general rule: over an N-year span, the number of leap days is <em>N / 4 - N / 100 + N / 400</em>, rounded down at
            each step, and adjusted slightly for how the span aligns with century boundaries. For most personal use, our engine
            handles this arithmetic for you.
          </p>

          <h2>Why some homemade calculators get this wrong</h2>
          <p>
            A shockingly common bug is calculating age with "days divided by 365". For someone born January 1, 1990, checking their
            age on January 1, 2026, the true age is exactly 36 years and 0 days. But if a calculator computes 13,149 days &divide; 365,
            it gets about 36.03 years and rounds down to 36 - correct by luck. Shift the same person to February 28 or March 1
            in different years and the rounding-luck goes away, and the number of "months remaining" starts to drift.
          </p>

          <p>
            The right fix is not "divide by 365.25" - it is calendar decomposition: count whole years, then whole months, then
            leftover days, using the calendar itself rather than an average. That is what our engine does, and it is why the
            year-month-day numbers you see match the ones a human reviewer would produce by counting on their fingers.
          </p>

          <h2>Edge cases worth knowing</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Born on February 29, calculating age on February 28 of a non-leap year.</strong> Our engine returns the
              age as of March 1 (i.e., increments the year on March 1). You will effectively see the "not yet had a birthday
              this year" result on February 28.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Long spans that cross a century.</strong> The 1900/2100 non-leap century years matter for people born in the
              late 1800s or projections into the late 21st century. Our engine handles the Gregorian rule for all supported browsers.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Historical dates before the Gregorian reform (1582).</strong> Different countries adopted the Gregorian
              calendar at different times. Our engine treats all dates using the modern Gregorian rule, which is standard for
              online calculators. For historical research work, consult a specialised source.
            </li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Try it yourself</h2>
          <p>
            Head to <a href="/#calculator">the calculator</a> and enter a leap-day date of birth (like February 29, 1996). Pick
            a few different calculate-at dates near the end of February in non-leap years and see how the result rolls over. If
            you would like the underlying math walked through in more detail, our companion article
            <a href="/guides/how-age-is-calculated">How Age Is Calculated</a> covers it end-to-end.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class={styles.related}>
      <div class="container">
        <div class={styles.relatedGrid}>
          <article class={`card ${styles.relatedCard}`}>
            <h3>How Age Is Calculated</h3>
            <p>The core calendar decomposition algorithm, in plain English.</p>
            <a href="/guides/how-age-is-calculated">Read guide -&gt;</a>
          </article>
          <article class={`card ${styles.relatedCard}`}>
            <h3>Age for Official Documents</h3>
            <p>Which age rules matter on passports, school forms, and job applications.</p>
            <a href="/guides/age-calculation-for-official-documents">Read guide -&gt;</a>
          </article>
          <article class={`card ${styles.relatedCard}`}>
            <h3>Days Between Dates</h3>
            <p>Counting exact days between two calendar dates without off-by-one bugs.</p>
            <a href="/guides/days-between-dates">Read guide -&gt;</a>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
